		<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-7333">
				<div id="div-comment-7333" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<cite class="fn">Caustic</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.loper-os.org/?p=55&amp;cpage=1#comment-7333">October 4, 2013 at 2:43 am</a></div>

		<p>Some evidence toward the futility of trying to implement a high level programming environment on current architectures is the comical situation of JS in the web browser. They tried to push JavaScript as the bottom level, only to find that the competition between different JITs (unsurprisingly) yielded the best improvements for a statically typeable subset of JS. They added typed arrays to JS while putting WebGL together and then someone got the &#8220;bright&#8221; idea of using them to implement C&#8217;s memory model. The eventual result was the specified &#8220;asm.js&#8221; subset, which is intended as a compile target for C, and which the browsers are starting to explicitly parse behind the scenes and do AOT compilation on. <img src='http://www.loper-os.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif' alt=';-)' class='wp-smiley' /> </p>

		<div class="reply">
		<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/?p=55&#038;replytocom=7333#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-7333", "7333", "respond", "55")'>Reply</a>		</div>
